<font color="#FF0000">MAYA LIN &amp; RACISM</font><br>
<tt>Fri Nov 29 14:34:19 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I watched the documentary about Maya Lin.  I have been waiting anxiously to see it for several reasons.  First of all, i am always interested in anything that will help enlighten me about the Vietnam era, since I was growing up at that time.  Second, I would love to visit Washington, mainly to see the wall.  My ex-boyfriend said that it was an emotional event.  Third, I was in college when the announcement was made for the competition that Maya Lin won.  I remember when her name was announced and the controvesy that followed.  I was at Boston U. and I'm sure that Ms. Lin and I are about the same age.  I was thrilled when she was picked because I couldn't believe that someone my age had received such an honor.  I was quickly dismayed to see the problems that arose with her triumph, especially the references made to her ethnic background, which was irrelevant and totally unfounded.  I thought that Ms. Lin was an example of what I thought my generation of women would become..confident &amp; successful.  I was rooting for her to overcome the narrow minded bigots.  When the tribute was completed, it was obvious to me, immediately that she had created a masterpiece..it was brilliant.  As an African-American, I was elated to know that she had been commissioned to create the monument for the Southern Poverty Law Center (which I have supported for many years).  There was no doubt in my mind that she was up to the daunting task, and seeing her beautiful tribute, I was not disappointed.  If Ms. Lin gets a chance to read this, I just want her to know that I am proud of all sje has accomplished and it is my goal to visit both of her monuments that commemorate the two biggest events of the 1960s.  Thank you for your quiet strength and courage.  It makes me feel so very small.
